<span class="name"><a name="92513"></a></span><span class="postdetails">#2:&nbsp;<font color=black><b></b> Author:&nbsp;<b>Jeradim</b>,&nbsp;</font></span><span class="postdetails"><font color=black></font></span>
<a href="viewtopic.php?p=92513#92513"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails"><font color=black>Posted: Mon Jan 10, 2005 11:05 am</font><span class="gen"><br>
</td></tr>
<tr><td class="printline">
<span class="postbody">I'm in agreement with the change that making a different quality spell makes a different lvl - appII for crude and shaped, appIII for normal and appIV for pristine - it makes sense really.
<br />
What doesn't make sense is that I have to make 10 appIII for my wholesaler and he only gives me 9sp for all of them.....but that's another story....
<br />
The more significant change is the way the skills/buffs stack with each other.  It used to be that you could stack 3-4 buffs between rounds which is no longer feasible.
<br />
You can't use more than 1 buff that enhances the same affect.
<br />
For example:
<br />
Tier 1 buffs enhance progress
<br />
Tier II buffs enchance durability.
<br />
So you can longer stack 2 buffs of the same tier in the same round, but you can still stack a tier 1 with a tier II to enhance both progress and durability.
<br />
Some power costs have been adjusted to so it's a good idea to review those.  When they first made the change the tier 1 alchemy skill experiment cost something like 109 power!  They took the servers down for a brief update and it was back to 31 after that.
<br />
All in all it makes it a bit tougher to make pristine but it's still very doable most of the time if you know what you are doing (and having the tier II/III etc. skills help too obviously)</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
</td></tr>
<br />
